Here's how you might implement this in Julia:

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (; average=nothing, max=nothing, min=nothing, trend=nothing)
    end

    stats = (; average=mean(temps), 
             max=maximum(temps), 
             min=minimum(temps))

    if length(temps) < 2
        return (; stats..., trend=:stable)
    elseif temps[1] < temps[end]
        return (; stats..., trend=:increasing)
    else
        return (; stats..., trend=:decreasing)
    end
end
```

This function first checks if `temps` is empty. If it is, we return a named tuple with all values set to `nothing`. If it's not, we calculate the average, maximum and minimum temperatures using functions from the `Statistics` module and store these in `stats`. Then, depending on the size of the temperature list and the relationship between the first and last temperature values, we determine whether the trend is increasing, decreasing or stable. We then return a named tuple with all our results.
